Khalid inserted the diagnostics terminal in the special slot; he waited
 for a few moments before his visor flashed a couple of green status icons
 and an embedded report.
 That was wrong though; it hadn't happened to him before, for a machine
 to be wrong, but it couldn't be anything other than wrong.
 According to the terminal, there was nothing wrong with the satellite.
 That only made Khalid shake his head in a show of frustrated disbelief.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reluctantly, he enabled the suit's communications and pinged Echo to accept
 his incoming call.
 Nothing happened.
 She's must still be mad at me, he thought, and set himself at running a
 full system diagnostic on the satellite, an even more rare occurence.
 That would take considerably more time, so he decided to let the terminal
 do its magic and do nothing but admire the scenery.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For someone born in the lush Saharan forest, space offered little to the
 eye; but Khalid always thought there was a feeling unattainable elsewhere.
 There was a singular sense of loneliness, yet a wonderful feeling of serenity
 that could only be attributed to God's presence.
 It was as if away from all the clutter and mess that Earth had become,
 space was like the desert of old: mostly empty and barren, but sometimes
 loving and fruitful.
 His rightful place to find God, Khalid always thought.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He then tried to reach Echo again; there was nothing on the ping.
 He brought up a verbose comms analysis on his visor display; his face soon
 became distraught.
 Echo wasn't blocking his pings; the signal never bounced back.
 It was as if the pod had gone dead.
 Khalid scanned with his visor's optronics frantically, his heart rate and
 oxygen consumption rising fast.
 The suit's life support subsystem began flashing warnings which became
 just another piece of visual clutter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Khalid focused towards where he'd thrown the box full of nanites, and magnified
 tenfold.
 Then, a hundred fold.
 The suit wasn't equipped with the full suite of sensors, so optical was
 his only choice.
 In the sharp, crisp darkness of the starless space, he could see nothing
 other than asteroid near and far, floating pieces of rock; in the background,
 the life-giving sun was but a bright writhing mass of yellow light.
 And in front of that background, some ways off, floated shiny little pieces
 of metal, glittering like a summer sea, sprawled across the void, growing
 ever more distant.
\end_layout

