\begin_layout Standard
It was then that Khalid saw the figure of a naked man wading in space without
 a suit, swimming towards him with the grace of a sea-creature.
 While his mind tried to make sense of the view, what struck him as odd
 wasn't the man was seemingly alive and well in the chilling void, nor that
 he seemed to have appeared out of nowhere.
 What struck Khalid as odd was that everyone knew that in space there was
 no medium to propel through, and trying to swim had no effect.
 Why is he swimming, thought Khalid and quickly amended his thought: Why
 is he swimming towards me?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A few yards away, he could clearly see the man's bearded face, eyes shining
 bright with an inner light.
 Hard shadows fell across his body as asteroids of all shapes and sizes
 intertwined above them in their invisible tracks in the sky.
 Yet there was a strange sense of perfection about him that felt natural,
 above everything else, even above the fact that it was impossible for a
 man to be doing what it appeared he was doing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A rush of the primal fleeing instinct threatened to overrun Khalid, the
 basic primal fear of the bizarre, the unknown, the paradoxical.
 Yet for the barest moment he held it in check and instead of trying to
 turn away and run with whatever pathetic thrust his suit could afford,
 he simply lay there, as if somehow everything was about to make sense.
\end_layout

